data.title: Australia may just be a death trap after all.

images.description:
TL/DR- mum drove home from work late at night and an Eastern Brown Snake wrapped around her wheel. She drove to a police station. 

We live in NSW Australia. My mum was on her way home from work tonight and on the way she saw a snake on the road. She thought she lined up the car properly to drive over it, and when she looked in the rear view mirror the snake was NOT on the road anymore. 

Luckily she spent 15 years living in the outback and knew exactly what to do when you think there’s a snake on a wheel at 9.30pm at night. She drove to the nearest police station and rang them from inside of her car and explained the situation, and asked them to help.

For anyone who isn’t aware, snakes can wrap around the front wheel, and as you get out of the car they can strike you. Not knowing how long they are, you don’t know how far to stay away so you just stay the fuck away.

Police were able to check it out and found the snake on the rear wheel. Police got my mum out and then decided to wait for Wires to come and attend to get the snake and identify it, as all they could see was a dark brown/black. Police had to stand and watch the car incase the snake moved or if  anyone went near it. Wires attended within the hour, confirmed it was an Eastern Brown Snake. 

So glad the police were able to quickly help my mum, and I’m so proud of her that she actually saw the snake in the first place and thought to go to police.

EDIT: I told my mum her snake story went viral. She apologises not taking photos of the snake at the time.  She wishes everybody safe trips home, and you can never be too careful.

data.title: Not gonna lie, this is a brag post.

images.description:
My best image yet. Went to a dark(ish) field this weekend and got some shots of the seagull nebula (IC2177). This is a very very faint and large nebula which is almost 2 degrees in width. I could only get maybe 1/3 of its entirety in the frame but what I did get came out pretty goood. 

Equipment used:
North Group 5" Triplet ED127 Refractor
EQ6Pro Mount
ZWO ASI1600mc-c CMOS camera

18x 300 sec stacked in Deep sky stacker and processed in photoshop.

EDIT: Thanks for the front page gang! Many have asked about the equipment I've used. I made a quick post breaking down my equipment bit by bit to explain what each part does.

data.description:
Junior in college here, hoping to join the police force post-graduation. To help with this decision, I've been signing up for ride alongs with my local PD to get an idea of what to expect. Go for a few, not much happens, everything's pretty low-key.

That is, until Friday night. 

Meet an officer at the station. He's a nice, young guy, only been on the force for a few months. The night is pretty uneventful, and we start to get towards the end of the shift when dispatch alerts us of a robbery-in-progress at a housing development near our location. As we pull up on the scene, he and I notice two different things at the same time. First, there are four individuals standing at the door of the house smoking and acting casual. Second, there's no backup. 

As we further approach the location, the individuals outside the house move away towards the sidewalk. My officer exits the vehicle and approaches the men, asking what they're doing, and then moves towards the house. The four men close in behind him.

He doesn't notice.

Sensing a threat, I start to move my hand to the radio when one of the individuals looks back towards the car, and we lock eyes. 

Eyes wide, he smacks his now tense companions to get their attention, and points back towards the car at me. Realizing my presence, they move away down the street. I lose visual.

Officer gets to the door, knocks, and when no one answers, he moves to the side of the house, but can't see anybody. He continues to stand by the front door for a few minutes. Backup still hasn't come. 

We then get another call from dispatch, stating that the person who called from that location is now reporting that there are men fighting outside his residence. My officer double checks his location, and we're at the right place. There's no one there, and there's definitely no fight going on.

My officer then asks dispatch to call the caller back and request that he meets him at the front door. "Sure thing," dispatch replies. There's then about a minute of silent tension, broken by the crackle of dispatch on the radio.

"The number has just been disconnected."

The hair on the back of my neck rises, and my officer rushes back to the vehicle. He gets on the phone with his supervisor, who instructs him to vacate the scene immediately. As we begin to pull out, the front door opens, and a man holding a knife watches us leave. We then see him greet the four men from before in a friendly manner from the rearview mirror as we drive away.

This was my first tense encounter on a ride along, and since I'm signed up for three more in the next two weeks, I'm sure it won't be my last. This ended up being a good scenario, as my officer ended his shift safe, albeit shaken. Had the four men not seen me, or decided to disregard my presence, it could have ended up much worse for him and myself. 

Without a doubt, there are bad cops out there. I've met a few in my time looking into the career path. But I wanted to share this experience with you all to give you an idea of what an officer may face while on the job. These guys are just trying to do their job and better their communities, and get home safe to their families at the end of watch. With all the stress that comes with the job, let's give them our support.

God bless, all. OP out.

#meme #police #scary #truestory #blueline

My dad has helped us in so many situations, I don't think I'll ever be able to repay him. He is my hero and I don't know what I'd do without him.

Whenever I needed a ride, he was there.
Whenever I needed anything, he was there. 
He bought me groceries when I couldn't leave my house and my SO was at work.
He drove in the middle of the night to my house because I was sick and alone.
When our car broke down and we couldn't afford replacement gear, he paid for it.
He did so much, I'd need 100 lifetimes to make it up. 

When he got stuck with a flat tire, we were down to driving the whole night if necessary to help him. He refused, said he'll be fine. He refused to tell us where he was. He's stubborn and too proud sometimes.

Dammit, dad. Let me help you for once.

Edit: Thanks for the FP, guys! 
The issue was that he got a flat tire and his spare was leaking air too. He drove 10-15 km, pulled over, inflated the spare, drove another 10-15 km. It broke my heart. We would have been more than glad to give him a lift or to find a 24h service to patch up the tire but nooooo......dad can handle it.

data.title: Sometimes I think my pets are tarded. But their job in life is to let me pet them, so that's ok.

images.description:
Pirañas. Amazon river. They are the cleaners of the river. They eat the dead and the sickly. They are a very important part of the ecosystem. 

In a fish tank they are boring until you feed them. One or two won’t cut it. 

You want to watch that kind of action you need to have a school of them like 10 or more only then will you see this behavior. 

in the river you are "safe" but in the dry season pirañas stranded in a small body of water quickly run out of food so they are starving, that’s when you don’t get in. You become their food. 

Anyway if you are in the Amazon river pirañas are the least of your problems.

Caymans (Amazon Gators) Anaconda the worlds largest serpent that lives in that river electric eels that will fry you, deadly insects like mosquitoes carrying malaria the list goes on and on. 

Piraña is the least of your problems.
